                    Video Game Makers Are Battling Sinking Stock Prices                
While air has seeped steadily from the stock market, it has poured from the four major publicly traded game publishers.










MARKET PLACE

                    A Bright Spot in the Dim Video Game Picture                
After Electronic Arts, the No. 1 video game publisher, announces what it has forecast will be disappointing results for the recent holiday quarter, expect a lot of hand-wringing about the future of the video game business. ''I don't think anyone should go into the earnings season with high expectations of a rosy picture, a rosy outlook or great numbers,'' said Edward S. Williams, a game industry analyst at Harris Nesbitt in New York. ''It was a very difficult holiday for the publishers as a whole, and the outlook is going to remain somewhat murky for at least a while.''











                    GameStop to Acquire Rival Video Game Retailer                
The GameStop Corporation, the nation's largest video game retailer, said yesterday that it had agreed to buy a rival, Electronics Boutique Holdings, for $1.44 billion. The combined company will have $3.8 billion in sales and more than 3,800 stores. GameStop's purchase will give it a quarter of the $11 billion video game market to compete with Wal-Mart Stores, which has 20 percent, according to Michael Pachter, an analyst with Wedbush Morgan Securities in Los Angeles.










COMPANY NEWS

                    BARNES & NOBLE WILL SPIN OFF ITS OWNERSHIP OF GAMESTOP                
Barnes & Noble said it would spin off its majority stake in GameStop, a retailer of video games. Barnes & Noble also cut its profit forecast for the year. Barnes & Noble said that it sold 6.1 million Class B shares of the video game chain back to the company for about $111.5 million. Barnes & Noble plans to distribute the remaining 59 percent stake, or 30 million shares, to its shareholders as a dividend. Barnes & Noble, which is based in New York, cut its full-year profit forecast because of the divesture of Game-Stop, which contributed more than half of its net income in the second quarter. Barnes & Noble received $37.5 million in cash and a three-year promissory note for $74 million from GameStop.


























